    ('Metereology Club','Academic/Honor Society','https://se-infra-imageserver2.azureedge.net/clink/images/263ee44e-b304-409e-9f9f-922451e98df44f8264e0-5371-4dba-b73b-0fa100ba7bfe.JPG?preset=small-sq','The Meteorology Club is a unique organization which provides services not only to its own members, but also to members of the campus community and to Long Island’s general public.   To serve the members of the organization, the Meteorology Club organizes trips to conferences, news studios, and the local National Weather Service office in Upton, NY.   These trips give club members opportunities to make connections with the professional world - connections which have proven to be quintessential in helping students find sectors of meteorology in which they are interested, and opening the doors to gain experience in those sectors.  In fact, visiting WABC-7 in NYC was such an inspiration for club members that some members took the initiative to collaborate with the School of Journalism and create, for the very first time, an actual Weathercasting class at Stony Brook University this semester.  This 1-credit class, taught by Jonathan Sanders, is just the start of what has the potential to become a strong broadcast meteorology program at the University.  The Meteorology Club also contributes to campus life by participating in the Involvement Fairs, social events, and campus events such as Earthstock and Roth Regatta.  The club has grown tremendously, from 5 active members to 25 active members in just 3 years.  And in addition to all the things I just mentioned, the group is dedicated to delivering the most reliable weather information to a public audience.Through the social media handle SBUWeather, the Stony Brook Meteorology Club provides the most accurate, relevant, and up-to-date weather forecasts for the local area.  Need to know the forecast for Roth Regatta?  Earthstock? Homecoming?  The Meteorology Club has it covered.  Want to know the chances of a snowday?  Need an optimistic reminder that winter does actually come to an end and the flowers will bloom again?   They provide that as well.   Meteorology Club weather updates can be found on Facebook (facebook.com/sbuweather) and Twitter (twitter.com/sbuweather).  The group also recently became a Weather Ready Nation Ambassador, meaning that the group is on a mission to educate the public about weather safety, and to help the National Weather Service pass along information which is meant to protect lives and property.  The Meteorology Club aims to alert the campus about impending weather hazards such as lightning, high winds, heavy rain, ice, and so on.  The group also visits students in primary and secondary education within the local area to teach them about weather safety.  The Meteorology Club has middle school and high school visits planned for April through June. The services provided by this exceptional organization transcend the bounds of the Meteorology Club and are shaping the academic opportunities of the University and the safety and well-being of the campus and surrounding communities.  ','E:  sbuweather@gmail.com','sbuweather@gmail.com','NA','NA','NA'),
